\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Health
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Health
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Health represents tangable, lasting damage to a character's body.
 Although most damage can get absorbed by energy, the GM may utilize Direct
 Damage
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Direct Damage
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Maximum Health 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximum health is eaqual to the total spent Attribute Points
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
attrubutes points, x.x.x
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Perminanent Wounds
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Perminant Wounds
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Death
\begin_inset Index idx
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Death
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once a character's health reaches or drops below 0, the character is dead.
 The good news is that death doesn't have to be perminent! This may be an
 opportunity for your friends to go on an adventure to revive you while
 you train in the afterlife and learn a new technique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, if the player desires, they may instead create a new character
 to be recruited by the adventuring party.
 Just know that it is a 
\emph on
choice
\emph default
 and not a neccessity.
\end_layout

